Date: Tue 6 Feb 2007 12:14:03 -0000
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Reuters [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L06455635.htm>

EU says banning UK poultry export is unjustified
-------------------------------------------------
Any move to ban British poultry exports after an outbreak of the
highly pathogenic H5N1 bird flu strain would be unjustified, the
European Commission said on Tuesday [6 Feb 2007]. "Any global ban on
the UK is totally disproportionate," a spokesman for the EU executive
told a regular briefing, adding it was satisfied with British
measures to contain the outbreak.
A number of countries have announced a ban on imports of British
poultry with others reportedly mulling over such a move. Earlier on
Tuesday [6 Feb 2007], South Korea and Hong Kong said they were
joining Russia and Japan in banning imports from Britain, while the
Financial Times reported that South Africa and Indonesia had followed
suit. EU member Ireland banned the import of poultry from Britain for
"gatherings and shows" as a precautionary measure. The ban does not
extend to British-ruled Northern Ireland.
The Commission said no further measures were planned at EU-level
following a meeting of the bloc's veterinary experts on Tuesday [6
Feb 2007]. "We are completely satisfied with the way the British
authorities reacted. They acted quickly once it was detected," the
spokesman said. "There is no need for a general ban ... trade should
continue within the internal market."
The spokesman said British officials had told an EU meeting in
Brussels it was unlikely the infection had come from Hungary, and
said that Britain had no plans for a widespread vaccination campaign.
[But see [4] below as to source identification. - Mod.MHJ]
