Date: Tue 6 Feb 2007 16:31:51 -0000
From: Christian Griot <christian.griot@ivi.admin.ch>
Source: AFP [edited]
<http://news.yahoo.com/s/afp/20070206/hl_afp/healthflueu_070206141657>

EU vets review bird flu defences
-------------------------------
EU veterinary experts were reviewing Europe's defences against deadly
bird flu amid fears that the virus could spread across the 27-nation
bloc after an outbreak in Britain. British officials briefed their EU
counterparts about actions they have taken at a routine meeting in
Brussels of food safety and veterinarian experts. But a European
Commission spokesman said Tuesday [6 Feb 2007] "no new measures are planned".
The outbreak of the virulent H5N1 strain of bird flu on a British
turkey farm came just weeks after the deadly virus was discovered on
a goose farm in southeastern Hungary, the 1st detection of the
disease in the European Union since last August [2006]. "The
commission is satisfied with the speed and efficiency of the UK
response to the outbreak as soon as a significant number of deaths
started appearing," spokesman Michael Mann told journalists. "The
authorities started reacting promptly."
Britain completed on Monday [5 Feb 2007] the slaughter of about 160
000 turkeys to keep the virus from spreading and authorities are
investigating how it was transferred to the birds.
The European Union adopted in February 2006 procedures to be taken in
the event the virus is detected after 14 member states were hit with
bird flu, causing a sharp drop in poultry consumption. Under those
rules, authorities are supposed to set up a 3-km (1.8-mile)
protection zone and a 10-km surveillance zone around the site of an outbreak.
Meanwhile, infected birds are supposed to be culled, other farmers
are supposed to keep poultry indoors and strict movement controls are
supposed to be put in place.
Despite the British measures to contain the virus, Britain was
slapped with poultry import bans by Japan, Russia, and Ukraine while
France, Ireland, the Netherlands, Norway, and Sweden have stepped up
precautions to prevent the spread of the virus. The commission
spokesman stressed that "global bans" from non-EU countries on
British poultry were "not justified" and said EU measures were
sufficient. "We will do everything we can to help to make sure that
these bans, or to try and help the UK makes sure that these bans last
as short a period as possible, because they are not justified," Mann said.
EU Health Commissioner Markos Kyprianou stressed on Monday [5 Feb
2007] that although other outbreaks among birds were likely in the
EU, a human pandemic was not about to sweep across the continent. "We
should remind ourselves that the virus is around so we will probably
have more outbreaks in the European Union in the future," he told
journalists. "We should look at it as an animal disease and should
not bring into the debate, even when there's an occasion, the issue
of a pandemic," Kyprianou said. "The possibility for a pandemic is a
totally separate issue."
--
